          "100000 EdNet-KT1 learners, 118971 Eedi learners, 10000 EdNet learners ",
          "EdNet, Eedi, ENEM",
          "Sequence of Answers, Problem Difficulty",
          "[Sequence of Answers, Option Scores]",
          "KT methods often estimate knowledge states based on correctedness of a MCQ. \n\nHowever, selecting different options may be indicative of different knowledge states. \n\nMoreover, while multi-task prediction has been used in KT, it lacks a full model specific for different tasks.",
          "The novelty of the approach is two-fold:\n\nThe introduction of option-weighting to assign different weights to the different possibilities of MCQ. \n\nSecondly, the model introduces the notion of mixtures-of-experts. \n\nOne Module Specific for KT, a second for OT and a thir for both tasks. ",
          "The authors create 2 forms of embeddings: a categorical embedding for exercises representation.\n\nA continuous embedding to represent the learners’ knowledge states. \n\nThe authors create mixture of experts set of embeddings. \n\nIn short, the authors create 3 modules that are meant to mimetize domain-experts with different perspectives:\n\n- Exercise Embeddings, \n- Exercise Analysis, \n- Learning State Recognition, \n- Interaction Parsing,\n- Knowledge State Acquisiton\n\nFor this exercise, there is an expert for the KT task and an expert meant to evaluate the KT and the OT perspectives. \n ",
          "DKT, DKVMN, SAKT, AKT, SAINT, CL4KT, DIMKT, DP-WEKT, MQFKT, ATDKT, WEKT",
          "Holdout Method",
          "EdNet\n{AUC: 0.7751 - WEKT, Accuracy: 0.7332 - WEKT, RMSE; 0.4218 - WEKT}\n\nEedi\n{AUC: 0.8164 - WEKT, Accuracy: 0.7538 - WEKT, RMSE; 0.4012 - WEKT}\n\nENEM\n{AUC: 0.7453- WEKT, Accuracy: 0.7350 - WEKT, RMSE; 0.4274 - WEKT}",
          "Results show that both WEKT and DP-WEKT approaches achieve state-of-the-art performance on 3 of the datasets.\n\nThe impact of the experts is measured via an ablation study - both for full experts and Expert Compents as well.",
          "Only works for MCQ scenarios.\n\nDoes not consider specific learner behaviors which may enrich the model’s performance.\n\nDoes not consider, at this stage, the incorporation of LLMs.\n\nHoldout Method"
        ],
