          "EdNet, Eedi, ENEM",
          "Sequence of Answers, Problem Difficulty",
          "[Sequence of Answers, Option Scores]",
          "KT methods often estimate knowledge states based on correctedness of a MCQ. \n\nHowever, selecting different options may be indicative of different knowledge states. \n\nMoreover, while multi-task prediction has been used in KT, it lacks a full model specific for different tasks.",
          "The novelty of the approach is two-fold:\n\nThe introduction of option-weighting to assign different weights to the different possibilities of MCQ. \n\nSecondly, the model introduces the notion of mixtures-of-experts. \n\nOne Module Specific for KT, a second for OT and a third for both tasks. ",
          "The authors create 2 forms of embeddings: a categorical embedding for exercises representation.\n\nA continuous embedding to represent the learners’ knowledge states. \n\nThe authors create mixture of experts set of embeddings. \n\nIn short, the authors create 3 modules that are meant to mimetize domain-experts with different perspectives:\n\n- Exercise Embeddings, \n- Exercise Analysis, \n- Learning State Recognition, \n- Interaction Parsing,\n- Knowledge State Acquisiton\n\nFor this exercise, there is an expert for the OT task and an expert meant to evaluate the KT and the OT perspectives. \n ",
